{{Infobox power station | name = Drammen Fjernvarme Heat Pump | image = Drammen Heat Pump.jpg | image_caption = The building containing the 14&nbsp;MW heat pump system. | image_alt = | location_map = | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|59.740833|10.23|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = Norway | location = [[Brakerøya]], [[Drammen]] | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = 2011 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = [[Drammen Fjernvarme]] | operator = | ps_heating_capacity= 14&nbsp;MW | ps_units_manu_model = | solar_site_area = | ps_electrical_capacity = | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_annual_generation = 67&nbsp;GWh (heat) | website = | extra = }}
'''Drammen Fjernvarme District Heating''' is a [[district heating]] system in [[Drammen]], [[Norway]], a regional capital some 65km west of [[Oslo]].
The heat pump was manufactured by Star Refrigeration in 2011<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/business-31506073 BBC News, UK; Heat pumps extract warmth from ice cold water]</ref> with 3 systems giving a combined capacity of 14 [[megawatt]]s to central [[Drammen]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Big Interview: Dave Pearson, Star Refrigeration |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/business/knowledge-for-growth/the-big-interview-dave-pearson-star-refrigeration.1392892118 |date=20 February 2014 |author=Antony Akilade |newspaper=Herald Scotland |accessdate=2014-02-28}}</ref> providing 85% of hot water needed for the city. The [[district heating]] system is owned and operated by [http://df.no/ Drammen Fjernvarme] who have the rights to the concession area given by the Drammen Municipality.<ref>{{citation |title=District heating with 90% Renewable Energy |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/sub/framtidensbyer/the-participating-cities-/drammen/district-heating-with-90-renewable-energ.html?id=548229 |publisher=Kommunal- og moderniseringsdepartementet |date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=2014-02-28}}</ref> This requires all new buildings larger than 1000&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup> to be built with a water-based heating system and connected to the district heating system.
The heat pump uses the natural refrigerant [[ammonia]] that has a zero [[global warming potential]] and is not a [[greenhouse gas]]. The heat source is seawater that is taken in around 8 or 9&nbsp;°C from a depth of 18&nbsp;m and is cooled by low pressure liquid [[refrigerant]]. Using a [[vapor-compression refrigeration]] cycle, the system heats district water from 65&nbsp;°C to 90&nbsp;°C for use in building heating and hot water systems. The system has an average [[coefficient of performance]] (COP) of 3.0 which means 1 unit of electricity is combined with 2 units of heat from the seawater to provide 3 units of heat to the district heating circuit. With the low cost of hydro-based electricity, it is cheaper to run a heat pump than a gas or electric boiler. In addition, the compressor technology used in the Drammen heat pump is the single screw compressor from Vilter (Emerson). Its internal design allows for balanced forces allowing it to perform with a very long bearing life at more than 120,000 hours for normal refrigeration compressors. <ref>Hoffman, & Pearson, D. 2011. [http://www.ammonia21.com/web/assets/link/Hoffman7thApril2011London%20colour.pdf Ammonia heat pumps for district heating in Norway 7 – a case study] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203054940/http://www.ammonia21.com/web/assets/link/Hoffman7thApril2011London%20colour.pdf |date=2013-12-03 }}. Presented at Institute of Refrigeration, 7 April, London.</ref>
The heat is extracted from a local [[fjord]] whose water temperature is around 8&nbsp;°C. The water is heated from recovered energy at a temperature of 120&nbsp;°C.<ref>[http://df.no/dokumenter/content/text_22eef578-b645-45cb-8c08-e5d1ba626be0/1403186536844/tekniske_bestemmelser_df2012.pdf Company Technical document in Norwegian, page 10)]</ref> A city ordinance requires most new buildings to exploit this form of heating.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/business-31506073 BBC News, UK; Heat pumps extract warmth from ice cold water]</ref>
