{{Infobox power station | name = Ernsthof Solar Park | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Germany | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|49|43|N|9|28|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = <ref>{{cite web|title=Ernsthof Solar Park in global mapping of solar power station site footprints|url=http://www.wiki-solar.org/map/sites/index.html?Ernsthof?u?15?49.707?9.481|publisher=Wiki-Solar|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> | country = Germany | location = [[Wertheim am Main|Wertheim]] | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = 2010 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = | operator = | solar_type = PV | solar_site_area = {{convert|85|ha|acre|0|abbr=on}} [http://www.wiki-solar.org/map/sites/index.html?Ernsthof?Pk60021?15?49.707,9.481 Site plan] | ps_electrical_capacity = 34.4 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = | extra = }} '''Ernsthof Solar Park''' is a [[photovoltaic power station]] near Dörlesberg, [[Wertheim am Main|Wertheim]], [[Germany]].<ref>[http://www.pvresources.com/PVPowerPlants/Top50.aspx Large-Scale Photovoltaic Power Plants] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101000000/http://www.pvresources.com/PVPowerPlants/Top50.aspx |date=January 1, 2016 }}</ref> It has a capacity of 34.4&nbsp;MWp making it the largest Solar Park in the state of Baden-Württemberg. Phase I of 6.88 MWp and covering an area of {{convert|16.6|ha}}, consisted of 31,280 modules by LDK Solar Energy Systems was completed on March 30, 2010. The second phase of 7.25 MWp was completed in December 2010,<ref>[http://www.ecos-energy.de/projekte/solarpark-ernsthof.html Solarpark Ernsthof]</ref> and it was expanded to 29.5 MW and then to 34.4 MW, with over 120,000 modules being fitted in December. Ernsthof East is 6.8 MW and Ernsthof West is 27.5 MW. The total area is {{convert|85|ha|acre|0|abbr=on}}. Ernsthof is part of the Tauberlandpark, a planned 72 MW solar park consisting of Ernsthof and Solarpark Gickelfeld (28 MW), which has been delayed due to the political uncertainty of solar parks of over 10 MW receiving the [[Feed-in tariffs in Germany|FIT]].<ref>[http://www.photovoltaik-guide.de/tauberlandpark-teilprojekte-des-solarparks-ernsthof-in-betrieb-15399 Teilprojekte des Solarparks Ernsthof in Betrieb]</ref><ref>[http://www.tauberlandpark.de/ProjektInformationen.asp?M=2&F=Off Der Tauberlandpark - solare Energie im Einklang mit der Natur]</ref> They may need, instead, to sign a [[Power Purchase Agreement]] with the [[Electricity sector in Germany#Grid|grid distribution power company]], which is better than subdividing large projects into multiple smaller segments just to qualify for the FIT.<ref>[http://www.fmlink.com/article.cgi?type=Magazine&title=Going%20Solar%3A%20Why%20Power%20Purchase%20Agreements%20Are%20a%20Low-risk%20Choice&pub=FMJ&id=40674&mode=source Going Solar: Why Power Purchase Agreements Are a Low-risk Choice]</ref>
